---
import Layout from "../layouts/Layout.astro";
import ChapterNav from "../components/ChapterNav.astro";
---

<Layout title="AI-Powered Code Auto-Fix Engine - Abaki">
    <main class="mx-auto max-w-4xl px-6 py-12 md:py-20">
        <a
            href="/abaki-overview"
            class="mb-8 inline-flex items-center text-sm font-medium text-indigo-400 hover:text-indigo-300"
        >
            <span class="mr-2">&larr;</span>
            Back to Abaki Overview
        </a>

        <article>
            <header class="mb-12">
                <h1
                    class="mb-4 text-4xl font-extrabold tracking-tight sm:text-5xl text-white"
                >
                    AI-Powered Code Auto-Fix Engine
                </h1>
                <p class="text-lg text-gray-400">
                    Building an async streaming HTTP client that communicates
                    with a Python AI service for code repairs
                </p>
            </header>

            <section class="prose prose-invert max-w-none space-y-8">
                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">Overview</h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
                        The AutoFix engine is the intelligence behind Abaki. It
                        communicates with an external Python service running AI
                        models (specifically Google's Gemini Flash) to analyze
                        code and suggest fixes. Rather than waiting for a single
                        response, Abaki streams tokens in real-time, allowing
                        the frontend to show live code suggestions as they're
                        being generated.
                    </p>
                    <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mt-4">
                        This was the most challenging component to build, as it
                        required mastering async streaming, handling event-based
                        responses, and coordinating between multiple services.
                    </p>
                </div>

                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">
                        Learning Journey
                    </h2>
                    <div class="space-y-3 text-gray-300">
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-1">
                                🔄 Challenge 1: Streaming HTTP Responses
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                Initially tried using regular
                                HttpClient.GetAsync(), which waits for the
                                entire response. Learned to use
                                HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead to
                                start processing before the response is
                                complete. This enabled true streaming behavior.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-1">
                                📡 Challenge 2: Server-Sent Events (SSE) Parsing
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                The Python service sends responses as
                                Server-Sent Events (SSE) format with event types
                                and data payloads. Spent time understanding the
                                "event:" and "data:" prefixes, handling line
                                breaks correctly, and buffering incomplete
                                lines.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-1">
                                ⚡ Challenge 3: Real-time Token Processing
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                Each token arrives asynchronously. Implemented
                                callback functions (onStatusReceived,
                                onTokenReceived, onDoneReceived) to handle
                                different event types. Learned about async
                                delegation patterns and proper error handling in
                                callback chains.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-1">
                                🛡️ Challenge 4: Error Resilience
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                The external service might disconnect or
                                timeout. Implemented proper exception handling,
                                retry logic, and graceful degradation. This
                                taught me the importance of defensive
                                programming when dealing with external services.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                        <div>
                            <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-1">
                                ✅ Key Learning
                            </h3>
                            <p>
                                Async streaming is powerful but complex.
                                Understanding HTTP completion options, proper
                                resource cleanup (using statements), and
                                callback-based event handling is crucial for
                                real-time systems.
                            </p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">
                        Key Code Implementation
                    </h2>

                    <div class="mb-6">
                        <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-3">
                            Streaming Request Setup
                        </h3>
                        <div
                            class="rounded-lg bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 overflow-hidden"
                        >
                            <pre
                                class="text-gray-300 text-sm p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code>{`// AutoFixService.cs
public async Task SendAutoFixStreamAsync(
    AutoFixRequest request,
    Func<Task>? onRequestSent = null,
    Func<string, StatusOrErrorPayload, Task>? onStatusOrErrorReceived = null,
    Func<TokenPayload, Task>? onTokenReceived = null,
    Func<DonePayload, Task>? onDoneReceived = null)
{
    if (request == null) 
        throw new BadRequestException("AutoFixRequest cannot be null.");

    _logger.LogInformation(
        "Sending AutoFix stream request to {Url} for repo {Repo}", 
        _streamUrl, 
        request.RepoUrl
    );

    var content = CreateJsonContent(request);
    using var requestMessage = new HttpRequestMessage(HttpMethod.Post, _streamUrl) 
    { 
        Content = content 
    };

    HttpResponseMessage response;
    try
    {
        // ResponseHeadersRead: Start processing BEFORE full response is received
        response = await _httpClient.SendAsync(
            requestMessage, 
            HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead
        );
        if (onRequestSent != null) 
            await onRequestSent.Invoke();
    }
    catch (HttpRequestException ex)
    {
        _logger.LogError(ex, "Failed to connect to Python service at {Url}", _streamUrl);
        throw new ExternalServiceException(
            $"Could not connect to AutoFix service: {ex.Message}"
        );
    }

    await EnsureSuccessResponseAsync(response);
}`}</code></pre>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mt-2">
                            HttpCompletionOption.ResponseHeadersRead is key—it
                            allows processing to begin without waiting for the
                            entire response body.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div class="mb-6">
                        <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-3">
                            Parsing Server-Sent Events
                        </h3>
                        <div
                            class="rounded-lg bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 overflow-hidden"
                        >
                            <pre
                                class="text-gray-300 text-sm p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code>{`// AutoFixService.cs - Stream Parsing
using var stream = await response.Content.ReadAsStreamAsync();
using var reader = new StreamReader(stream);

string currentEvent = "message";
var parseOptions = new JsonSerializerOptions { PropertyNameCaseInsensitive = true };

while (!reader.EndOfStream)
{
    var line = await reader.ReadLineAsync();
    if (string.IsNullOrWhiteSpace(line)) 
        continue;

    // Extract event type (event: status, event: token, etc.)
    if (line.StartsWith("event:"))
    {
        currentEvent = line.Substring(6).Trim();
    }
    // Extract JSON data payload (data: {...})
    else if (line.StartsWith("data:"))
    {
        var rawJson = line.Substring(5).Trim();

        // Check for stream termination
        if (rawJson == "[DONE]") 
            break;

        try
        {
            switch (currentEvent.ToLowerInvariant())
            {
                case "status":
                case "error":
                    var statusData = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<StatusOrErrorPayload>(
                        rawJson, 
                        parseOptions
                    );
                    if (statusData != null && onStatusOrErrorReceived != null)
                        await onStatusOrErrorReceived(currentEvent.ToLowerInvariant(), statusData);
                    break;

                case "token":
                    var tokenData = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<TokenPayload>(
                        rawJson, 
                        parseOptions
                    );
                    if (tokenData != null && onTokenReceived != null)
                        await onTokenReceived(tokenData);
                    break;

                case "done":
                    var doneData = JsonSerializer.Deserialize<DonePayload>(
                        rawJson, 
                        parseOptions
                    );
                    if (doneData != null && onDoneReceived != null)
                        await onDoneReceived(doneData);
                    break;
            }
        }
        catch (JsonException ex)
        {
            _logger.LogWarning(ex, "Failed to parse SSE payload: {Payload}", rawJson);
        }
    }
}
`}</code></pre>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mt-2">
                            The SSE format requires parsing "event:" and "data:"
                            prefixes and handling JSON deserialization for each
                            payload.
                        </p>
                    </div>

                    <div>
                        <h3 class="text-indigo-300 font-bold mb-3">
                            Using the Stream with Callbacks
                        </h3>
                        <div
                            class="rounded-lg bg-gray-900 border border-gray-700 overflow-hidden"
                        >
                            <pre
                                class="text-gray-300 text-sm p-4 overflow-x-auto"><code>{`// RepoController.cs - Consuming the Stream
public async Task<IActionResult> TriggerAutoFixAsync(int id, [FromBody] AutoFixRequest request)
{
    var repo = await _repoService.GetByIdAsync(id);
    if (repo == null)
        return NotFound();

    try
    {
        // Define callbacks to handle stream events
        await _autoFixService.SendAutoFixStreamAsync(
            request,
            
            onRequestSent: async () =>
            {
                _logger.LogInformation("AutoFix request sent to Python service");
            },
            
            onStatusOrErrorReceived: async (eventType, status) =>
            {
                _logger.LogInformation("Status: {Message}", status.Message);
                // Broadcast to connected WebSocket clients via SignalR
                await _hubContext.Clients.All.SendAsync("Status", status);
            },
            
            onTokenReceived: async (token) =>
            {
                _logger.LogDebug("Token received: {Token}", token.Token);
                // Stream each token to frontend in real-time
                await _hubContext.Clients.All.SendAsync("Token", token);
            },
            
            onDoneReceived: async (done) =>
            {
                _logger.LogInformation("AutoFix complete");
                await _hubContext.Clients.All.SendAsync("Done", done);
            }
        );

        return Ok(new { message = "AutoFix processing complete" });
    }
    catch (ExternalServiceException ex)
    {
        _logger.LogError(ex, "AutoFix service failed");
        return StatusCode(503, new { error = "AutoFix service unavailable" });
    }
}`}</code></pre>
                        </div>
                        <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mt-2">
                            Callbacks are async functions that handle each
                            event. SignalR broadcasts updates to all connected
                            clients in real-time.
                        </p>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">
                        Technology Stack
                    </h2>
                    <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
                        {
                            [
                                "C#",
                                "HttpClient",
                                "Server-Sent Events",
                                "Async/Await",
                                "StreamReader",
                                "JSON Serialization",
                                "SignalR",
                                "Callbacks",
                            ].map((tech) => (
                                <span class="rounded-full border border-indigo-500/30 bg-indigo-500/10 px-4 py-2 text-sm font-medium text-indigo-300">
                                    {tech}
                                </span>
                            ))
                        }
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div>
                    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-white mb-4">
                        Results & Impact
                    </h2>
                    <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
                        The AutoFix engine provides:
                    </p>
                    <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 mt-3">
                        <li class="flex items-start">
                            <span class="text-indigo-400 mr-3">✓</span>
                            <span
                                ><strong>Real-time Code Suggestions:</strong> Users
                                see AI-generated fixes as tokens arrive, not after
                                full completion</span
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li class="flex items-start">
                            <span class="text-indigo-400 mr-3">✓</span>
                            <span
                                ><strong>Efficient Streaming:</strong> No waiting
                                for the entire AI response before showing results</span
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li class="flex items-start">
                            <span class="text-indigo-400 mr-3">✓</span>
                            <span
                                ><strong>Event-Driven Architecture:</strong> Different
                                event types (status, token, error, done) allow flexible
                                handling</span
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li class="flex items-start">
                            <span class="text-indigo-400 mr-3">✓</span>
                            <span
                                ><strong>Error Resilience:</strong> Proper exception
                                handling ensures failures don't crash the entire system</span
                            >
                        </li>
                        <li class="flex items-start">
                            <span class="text-indigo-400 mr-3">✓</span>
                            <span
                                ><strong>Scalable Communication:</strong> Uses callbacks
                                for loose coupling between service and controller</span
                            >
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </div>
            </section>
            <ChapterNav
                prevLink="/abaki-github"
                prevText="GitHub Integration"
                nextLink="/abaki-database"
                nextText="Database Architecture"
            />
        </article>
    </main>
</Layout>
